Why Styx wins: The Styx compilation checks almost every box from my list. It’s a single‑disc, tightly sequenced hits set with consistent mastering and flow, which matches my preference for coherent sequencing and consistent loudness for replayability. The description explicitly calls out guitar‑forward mixes, cutting mids and stacked multi‑part choruses/ layered harmonies — all core AOR ingredients I prize (strong melodic vocals, multilayered vocal stacks and punchy multi‑tracked guitars). The compilation’s “spacious yet polished arena sound” and “loud‑but‑faithful” mastering align with my taste for polished, arena‑scale production that still preserves punch and vocal clarity. In short, it delivers hook‑centred, singable tracks with studio craft and upfront vocals that cut through — exactly the mic‑forward, amp‑forward, melodic rock profile I favor.
Why Back in Black is rejected: While Back in Black is an excellent, riff‑forward record with cutting mids and punchy attack (which I appreciate to an extent), the candidate’s strengths are exactly the aspects I flag as less desirable: the remaster preserves “roomy band‑in‑the‑room energy” and “dynamic, uncompressed live grit.” That roominess and live grit risk the “gritty, loose” feel that can reduce instrument separation and bury the vocal‑foreground clarity I prefer. Back in Black is more about raw riff attack and live tone than the multilayered vocal stacks, meticulous studio sheen and tight single‑disc sequencing that I specifically value. For those reasons — despite great riffs and preserved transients — the Styx compilation is the better fit for my stated production and sequencing preferences.

